Very Bad Experience

I took my 2 small dogs to this place a couple of months ago.  Since the first interaction, I noticed the cashier was recommending way too many services that I did not request.  I accepted most of them (like teeth cleaning, ears cleaning, nails cutting, etc.) always thinking I wanted my babies to be pampered and look nice when they were ready to be picked up. I noticed the receptionist/cashier kept telling me about the cost of a ‚ÄúFlea Treatment‚Äù, without not even knowing if my pets needed it or not. I firmly told her my doggies did not have any fleas. ‚ÄúI check them on a daily basis. I am sure they don‚Äôt have any fleas‚Äù, I said. When it was time to pick them up, I was told that both of my dogs were infested with fleas and that both received the Flea Treatment. To make the long story short, the cashier informed the services rendered grand total was $149.00.   I fell robbed!  I never authorized such treatment for my dogs, which I was sure had no fleas at ALL!  I had to pay anyway to get my dogs back. I love my dogs like they were my own children. I will pay for any service I consider they need, but paying for something they did not need was very dishonest, unfair and unprofessional.  Pet lovers:  Be aware of this so called ‚ÄúPet Grooming Service‚Äù!!!< /Text>

I snapped them back into place and checked again for codes and the code was gone.
The smog guy was a jerk.  He was rude and condescending, walked away while I was talking to him and just had a general crappy attitude.
I went to another smog place (test only) and it passed.  I didn't have to wait 3 hours either, like I did at this place.  Needless to say, I won't be going back there.< /Text>< userid>

< Text>
I hope you take the time to read my short book. Sadly, I have nothing good to say about Econo Firestone any longer. 6 years ago I had posted a 5 star review after they had serviced my Dodge truck and my wife's car. My brother, my son, and my employees were also taking their vehicles to them. Because six years ago they did good work with a quick turn around and backed up the work they did. Unfortunately, that is no longer the case. I followed my son to Econo a month ago to drop off his truck due to a check engine light on the dash. They tested and said it was a catalytic converter problem. They also said he needed a new timing chain. My son told them that the truck had also been over heating. So please fix that also. Now mind you. They replaced both catalytic converters in 2013. Approximately 2 years ago, they replaced one of them again. But they claimed that this one was not one they had replaced prior. In fact for longest time they denied that they had replaced both catalytic converters until I told them to check thoroughly on their computer. Well, they found it. So several weeks later. My son still doesn't have his truck back, (Which they know, he uses for work most every day). They told him that they don't have a special tool they need to replace the timing chain. Said they had ordered the tool and were waiting to receive it.  But everything else has been repaired, including a new radiator and thermostat. After a third week waiting my son took his truck back. Still needing the timing chain replaced, he took it to the closest reputable auto repair shop near him. They had the timing chain replaced, and back to him in one day. It didn't take my son long to find that the overheating problem he had paid to be repaired, was still a problem. He took it back to Econo. They claimed it needed a new radiator cap. Said that they replaced it and it no longer overheats. He had already paid them to replace the entire radiator. Why wouldn't they have put on a new and correct cap? He got the truck back a couple days later, to find that it was still over heating. He took his truck back to the place that installed the new timing chain in one day, and they found that the thermostat was stuck and they replaced it. Meaning that my son's truck probably didn't need the new radiator or the new cap. His truck no longer overheats. He drove the truck over 50  miles to make sure that the dash sensor light stayed off, so his truck would pass a smog test. The dash engine light came back on. After paying Econo over $2,000 at this point, and them never being able to replace the timing chain. My son was getting irritated. Now I want you to know that Econo Firestone mechanics are the only people to work on the catalytic converters of my son's truck period. Well after he and I took his truck back to Econo yesterday morning, for the sensor light problem.  We were told there must be a short in the wiring to the sensors. At this point, we are livid. Myself, my son, my employees and all of my family are done with Econo Firestone on Arlington Avenue in Riverside. We will never take a vehicle to them again. If you don't want to be a victim of shoddy and incomplete repairs. Then I suggest you find a different auto repair shop. Life can be difficult as it is. Why ad unnecessary aggravation to the mix?</Text>

< Time>
1523828222318< /Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate><Review>Decided to try Magellan's after multiple locals recommended. Small wine selection but fabulous and to the point, full bar. Hard to find parking, even on a Tuesday. Fragrant, warm bread on request, but cold butter. Not too annoying, as the bread was lovely. Now, the revelations! Caprese salad had beautiful beefsteak tomatoes and a high-quality mozzarella with a tasty balsamic reduction, and perfect basil chiffonade. On to the filet with peppercorn sauce and a red wine Demi-glace: I cannot express how impressed I am that the chef chose to use green peppercorns! That's typically how I made kangaroo with a green peppercorn sauce in Europe, but it was a learning experience for me to have this presented on filet mignon. Appreciated the addition of fresh parsley to the sauce. Absolutely brilliant!!! I suggest a deep Cabernet or at least a Merlot to bring out that peppercorn, I had a Pinot noir. It was absolutely to die for. The vegetables were an excellent accompaniment with a bit of broccoli, red onion, pepper and larger diced potato- everything was seasoned well and cooked perfectly.

Side note: Magellan's is one of the few restaurants that doesn't need salt and pepper on the table as everything is perfectly seasoned and salted, but they are unpretentious enough to offer it. Loved this!

All in all, we are extremely well fed and satisfied which is what anyone wants from fine dining. We are happy to have found this in Tracy and will return for the duck and lamb. Thank you, Magellan's, for a wonderful evening of spectacular food! Thomas, we enjoyed your company and will return very soon.< /Review><Pics>None</Pics><response>None</response>< gmap_id>

< review>
We had been recommended this spot for a great lobster and prawns .. our service was poor.. for 45$ we expected a full size Lobster tail.. and more then 3 prawns.. it's started with us being seated and asked if we would like a few mins to order.. never asked us if we would like water or anything to drink before we looked at the menu.. then we were asked if we were ready to order after ordering we were then offered our drinks.. then as the second waiter brought out the appetizer mind u 13$ for grilled scallops and we got 4 tiny scallops not the bay scallops we assumed we were paying for.. he is the one who offered bread and butter.. then when got the bread and butter the bread was warm but the butter was frozen?? Then I received my refill of my iced tea and it had a few pieces of bread floating in the bottom. I grabbed the attention of the hostess and she immediately grabbed the drink then showed the waiter and he returned with bread drink in hand and asked if I added any sugar to thins drink cause sometimes the sugar clumps at the bottom. I told him I added it to the first glass and this was a refill.. he then states hhhmm that's a first.. not an apology not a I'm sorry let me get that for u...If I knew I'd receive grief for asking for a non breaded drink I would have ordered a 5$ bud light.. yes 5$ bud light.. Then our "waiter" was serving us with a blue tooth in his ear. We thought this was completely un -professional. Then the food finally came out and that's when we saw the baby lobster tail filleted out to look bigger. I feel like we were definitely not treated like they wanted us to return and for 100$ bill for 2 people that was hard to believe the lack of care for patrons. Needless to say we will never return there ever again.</review>

<time>1458962141306</time><Pics>None< /Pics><userid>118149366197721734422<//userid>< user_name>
Steph Rondi</user_name>

< Text>
Based on a friends recommendation we choose to try Magellan's on our way home through Tracy to have a nice dinner before our teens started school.

We called and made reservations to stop for dinner on our way home from a great day boating on the lake. We arrived with a party of 6 at 7:40 on a Friday evening. We were the biggest party in the restaurant. We were seated immediately by the hostess. She poured us water while we looked at the menus. We had a few questions and her response in an unpleasant tone was "I don't know, I am the hostess".  If you can't answer how about, I AM SORRY you will have to ask your server.

Our waiter came over and asked if we wanted drinks, we said, "no but we were ready to order". He asked again about drinks, we told him we had been out in the sun all day and really just wanted water. The look on his face was one of aggravation.
We pushed again for him to take our orders which he did. This waiter did not crack a smile or pleasant look. Some of us ordered salads which came quickly.

Then almost 50 MINUTES after we ordered with no check-in from our waiter. We sat at our table fading fast and not one word of apologies from anyone. There was another waitress who walked around with a scowl on her face and the hostess looked frustrated as she reset tables.
We heard a bell ring and knew it was our food. Our waiter was making bar drinks for another table and sent the other waitress to start bringing our food. The look on both faces were that of exacerbation. I am not sure what we did to deserve such visibly aggravated staff.

Finally, our meals came, 4 of the 6 meals were similar pasta dishes, one was veal and one was filet. This should not have taken 50 minutes. The food was ok, not anything great after such a wait, not anything I would travel back to have or recommend to others. We finished our meals and were exhausted and ready to go. Our waiter asked about dessert, when we said, "no thank you", he again showed how frustrated he was.. We asked to have food wrapped up, my husband asked for a couple of slices of bread from the table to be added to his box. The hostess was nice enough to fulfill this request. I watched in the open servers area as our waiter approached her and openly showed his frustration that she was slicing bread for the box.

It was a little after 9 pm, we paid our pricey bill with hefty gratuity included because we were a party of 6. At this point the owner was in the dining room talking to guests. He said  to us as we began to depart, "that was fast."
Sir if you think a ticket time of 50 minutes is fast you are sadly mistaken. Had we not had to wait so long we probably would have had a few desserts and coffee.
The staffs disdain just made me feel that I wanted to get out, why would we want to linger with such a negative vibe in the space.

Even the two teens with us knew the wait staff was not treating us like we were paying customers and the service and wait would not be okay on any food network reality show.

We eat out a great deal and have had many kinds of dining experiences. I can't remember a time when 24 hours later I still NEEDED to write a bad yelp review. The owner should visit some of the best restaurants in Livermore or Pleasanton to experience good service, happy staff and delicious food for the same price of Magellan's. Perhaps just watching food network will give you some clues.

Sorry we gave it a try and will not return, we will keep driving next time.</Text>

< text>
Three Pickles on Canon Perdido has so many things going for it besides having the best sandwiches in town. First of all, it has some of the best views in Santa Barbara when you sit in the patio/alley. It's next to the best coffee shop in town, Handlebar. And best of all, the Pickles bar (located in a historic building that once housed an opium den and brothel) has an all star team of bartenders all with different specialties. I find myself there for breakfast, lunch and dinner for drinks! It's a real gem.<//text>

<Review>(Translated by Google) The Handlebar Coffee Roaster, which is next to each other, and the outdoor table side by side, make the outside feel better than the interior. The sandwiches are not greasy and lighter than people imagined by the photos they posted. My husband ate Meatball, and I ate Reuben, but the processed meat called pastrami from Leuven is sour-kraut (German pickled cabbage), which is well neutralized in terms of taste. Italian Wedding Soup is a complete seaweed soup. It is recommended that you try it. ^^ But you should never eat cucumber pickles that you take by yourself at the store. Weave I just squeeze the garden salad and it tastes bad in my mouth.

Well, we come here quite often and order the same thing every time... we can‚Äôt possibly order faster. But in her unduly extreme sense of urgency, she rushed through our orders and COMPLETELY messed mine up. I asked for a mix of sauces with ‚Äújust a TINY bit of eel sauce.‚Äù And she doused it. There‚Äôs no recovery once the sauce is on there. And of course I felt so pressured by her behavior that I didn‚Äôt ask for it to be redone (huge regret). <Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
A meal per person costs $115 with supplementary grilled Wagyu Beef for an extra $25. They serve around 8 people a day so make a reservation before you come. Food is delicately handmade, but adjusted slightly to fit American tastebuds. The chef himself creates his pickled ingredients from scratch. The imported ingredients from Japan are blended well with the fresh ingredients available locally. My favourite is probably their steamed dish. The menu changes monthly.</Review>

<date>1573256609120</date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
What a fabulous dining experience for two hours. Each our little dishes are well presented and absolutely delicious. OzaOza is the only Japanese Restaurant in San Francisco that provide authentic Kaiseki cuisine ‰ºöÂ∏≠ÊñôÁêÜ.

Little bit background about Kaiseki cuisine.
There are two kinds of traditional Japanese meal styles called kaiseki . The first, where kaiseki is written as ‰ºöÂ∏≠ refers to a set menu of select food served on an individual tray (to each member of a gathering). The second, written as ÊáêÁü≥ refers to the simple meal that the host of a chanoyu gathering serves to the guests before a ceremonial tea.

OzaOza changes menu every month based on the seasonal ingredients.

**2/2019 Menu w/supplemental dish  (some highlights of the set)
Sakizuke (small Appetizer): Love the combination of herring roe, dried squid and yuzu  skin.
Yakimono (Grilled dish):  the miso marinated grilled butterfish are stunning.
Supplemental dish:  The boom,  Waygu beef steak was mind blowing. We glad that we ordered the waygu steak as a brief interlude for our wonderful night.
Sunomono (Vinegared Dish): the best sunomono that the I ever had, the sweet miso- mustard sauce was phenomenal

Drinks:
Plum Wine: Nanbu Baji, very unique taste of the plum wine that OzaOza Provided, it has some sweet osmanthus taste< /Text>

<rating>5< /rating><Review>This was also my first Kaiseki experience, and it was awesome! All the food was absolutely delicious, with ingredients & preparation methods I hadn't even seen before - and I've eaten a lot of food in my life, haha.

The service was phenomenal, really friendly and not at all pushy, she explained everything very well and it felt very special without being too 'fussy', which is just how I like it.

It was also a great value considering the amount of work & care put into each dish, and the quality of the ingredients - really lovely sashimi for example, including uni from Japan that tasted so light and delicious I think it'd make an uni lover out of anyone. We opted to add the Wagyu beef course for an additional $20, and if you're a beef lover I think it'd be well worth it - it was the most tender beef I'd ever had that still maintained a savory flavor.

Definitely left feeling satisfied in every way, and I'm looking forward to going back again!< /Review>< pics>
None</pics>

<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
This was also my first Kaiseki experience, and it was awesome! All the food was absolutely delicious, with ingredients & preparation methods I hadn't even seen before - and I've eaten a lot of food in my life, haha.
The service was phenomenal, really friendly and not at all pushy, she explained everything very well and it felt very special without being too 'fussy', which is just how I like it. It was also a great value considering the amount of work & care put into each dish, and the quality of the ingredients - really lovely sashimi for example, including uni from Japan that tasted so light and delicious I think it'd make an uni lover out of anyone. We opted to add the Wagyu beef course for an additional $20, and if you're a beef lover I think it'd be well worth it - it was the most tender beef I'd ever had that still maintained a savory flavor. Definitely left feeling satisfied in every way, and I'm looking forward to going back again!< /text>

Irene Leung<//username>
< time>
1596671206231<//time>
< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< review>
After a few months of Stay At Home, I decided to venture out to the Bob's Big Boy in Norco.   I am fan of Big Boy's Hamburger since I was about 5 - 6 years old.     I was born and raised in Pasadena.  My parents would go to the Bob's Big Boy on Colorado.  We either ate in the small take out patio or took the burgers home.   Pasadena did have 3 Bob's Big Boy.     Two on Colorado Blvd. and 1 on Lake Ave.   I do miss them.  Even the ones in Barstow, CA are closed now.  There is only 3 left here.  The original in Burbank, CA, Downey, CA and Norco, CA.

We drove down to Norco for lunch.   I called ahead to make sure they have dine-in service.  They do have dine-in service.  We were greeted by the host and seated right away.  The waitress was very courteous, attentive and very friendly.

She took our drink orders and we were ready to order.  I had their Big Boy combo (regular size) not the jumbo size one.

Salad was fresh.  The burger came with fries.   I truly enjoyed the Big Boy hamburger.  It's been a while since I ate one too.

The server kept on coming back making sure drinks were filled and making sure we were happy with food.

I would recommend this place.   Very close to the freeway too.

I would go back to Bob's Big Boy again.<//review>

Apparently when Marie callender's closed their restaurant in Corona Bob's big boy Norco figures that they can slack and they won't lose any business to the competition little did they know but Bob's big boy Norco is losing business. We have ordered the same takeout dinners from this restaurant a few times and tonight it got to the point where I just had to post a review on Yelp and now on Google. <name>Karen Mahan</name>< Text>
I've been coming to Bob's Big Boy since I was a small kid and we still make special trips out of our way to eat here. This is my favorite burger (sorry In-n-Out!)  I have ONLY had the Big Boy Classic Burger and their Fudge Cake dessert...EVER, so can't attest to their other food offerings, but they have a small salad bar and a large menu. You can get your drinks made with Vanilla or Cherry. They serve Pepsi products unfortunately...sad.
I just know this is comfort food for me! They have a 50's vibe inside with booths and tables in red, white and blue decor.   Service is fast and great most of the time.  They sometimes have Car Shows in there large parking lot.  There is a " Malt and Ice Cream Shoppe" inside the restaurant with a small gift shop selling cookies, candy T-Shirts and gifts.  This is "Americana" modernized!
Did you know that the Bob's Big Boy statue which stands outside the Norco restaurant, is the only one to have their " Bob's mascot" altered? They received special permission to add the cowboy hat on Bob!  Norco is "Horsetown USA" where the horses outnumber the people.< /Text>

105984218453756983853< /userid>
<review>In ancient times, Bob's Big Boy restaurants herds roamed the plains in abundance.
Then came the dark times when evil corporations ran the chain into the ground.
Today there are few remaining Bob's Big Boys left in the wild. The iconic Big Boy combo with the Bleu Cheese dressing of my childhood is now a rarity as stores in Diamond Bar close.  There are only a handful of stores left. This store was not crowded on a Saturday night, which makes me worry about its future. I'm sure the original Toluca Lake store will be around forever...but please people, visit all the stores so that you and your progeny can experience an American classic.< /review><gmapID>0x80dcc9e418783719:0x68fa77f84e702fa0<//gmapID>< response>

<time>1526183665508</time><review>In ancient times, Bob's Big Boy restaurants herds roamed the plains in abundance.
Then came the dark times when evil corporations ran the chain into the ground.
Today there are few remaining Bob's Big Boys left in the wild. The iconic Big Boy combo with the Bleu Cheese dressing of my childhood is now a rarity as stores in Diamond Bar close.  There are only a handful of stores left. This store was not crowded on a Saturday night, which makes me worry about its future. I'm sure the original Toluca Lake store will be around forever...but please people, visit all the stores so that you and your progeny can experience an American classic.</review><GmapID>0x80dcc9e418783719:0x68fa77f84e702fa0<//GmapID><pics>None<//pics>< userid>
